## 7. Non-Functional Requirements

### 7.1 Performance

- Simulations should feel smooth and target 60fps where animation is continuous.
- Time-based simulation code should avoid stale closures.
- Intervals and animation frames must be cleaned up on unmount.
- Visual state arrays should be pruned to prevent unbounded growth.

### 7.2 Responsiveness

- Feed and article views must work on mobile, tablet, and desktop.
- Complex sandboxes may be optimized for desktop interaction, but they must remain readable on smaller screens.
- Widget layouts should collapse predictably rather than overflowing.

### 7.3 Accessibility

- Use high-contrast colors for text and technical indicators.
- Buttons and interactive controls must have clear focus states.
- Inputs should have labels.
- Color should not be the only carrier of critical meaning.
- Icon-only controls should include accessible names.

### 7.4 Maintainability

- Keep widgets self-contained.
- Keep post metadata centralized.
- Prefer structured data over hard-coded visual branches.
- Use concise component names that describe the Android concept being taught.

## 8. Content Requirements

Each post should include:

- A concrete Android engineering problem.
- A short conceptual model.
- One interactive widget.
- At least one failure mode or misconception.
- A practical takeaway for production Android work.

The prose should be technical, compact, and specific. Avoid generic tutorial language when the widget can demonstrate the behavior directly.

## 9. Future Roadmap

### 9.1 Memory Leak Visualizer

A heap-style widget showing object references. Objects retained past their expected lifecycle should turn into leak candidates with a clear ownership path.

### 9.2 Jetpack Compose vs. XML Toggle

A code-diffing visualizer that compares equivalent UI implementations in XML Views and Jetpack Compose.

### 9.3 Thread Lane Visualizer

A dispatcher simulation showing how `Dispatchers.Main`, `Dispatchers.IO`, and CPU-bound work move through different execution lanes.

### 9.4 View Measurement Explorer

A layout pass visualizer for `onMeasure`, `onLayout`, and `onDraw`, including examples of nested layout cost.

## 10. Phase 1 Acceptance Criteria

- The feed displays at least two posts.
- Clicking a post opens a detail view and scrolls to the top.
- The detail view renders technical prose and one sandbox.
- `Flow.debounce()` sandbox supports manual emissions and debounce delay changes.
- Lifecycle sandbox supports step-through lifecycle progression.
- Simulations clean up intervals or animation frames on unmount.
- The UI remains usable on desktop and tablet widths.
- Primary text and controls meet high-contrast dark-mode accessibility expectations.
